{"parse":{"title":"ACTFL Proficiency Guidelines","pageid":1679129,"revid":803492889,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>ACTFL Proficiency Guidelines</b> were created by the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Council_on_the_Teaching_of_Foreign_Languages\" title=\"American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages\">American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages</a> in order to provide a means of assessing the <a href=\"/wiki/Language_proficiency\" title=\"Language proficiency\">proficiency</a> of a <a href=\"/wiki/Foreign_language\" title=\"Foreign language\">foreign language</a> speaker.\n</p><p>The guidelines are broken up into different proficiency levels: novice, intermediate, advanced, superior, and distinguished. Additionally, each of these (except superior and distinguished) is further subdivided into low, mid and high.  These proficiency levels are defined separately for ability to listen, speak, read and write. Thus, in those American programs that emphasize written language over spoken, students may reach the advanced level in reading and writing while remaining at a lower level in listening and speaking.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=ACTFL_Proficiency_Guidelines&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Task-based_language_learning\" title=\"Task-based language learning\">Task-based language learning</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Common_European_Framework_of_Reference_for_Languages\" title=\"Common European Framework of Reference for Languages\">Common European Framework of Reference for Languages</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_language_benchmarks\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Canadian language benchmarks\">Canadian language benchmarks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Defense_Language_Proficiency_Tests\" title=\"Defense Language Proficiency Tests\">Defense Language Proficiency Tests</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Oral_Proficiency_Interview\" title=\"Oral Proficiency Interview\">Oral Proficiency Interview</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=ACTFL_Proficiency_Guidelines&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.sil.org/lingualinks/LANGUAGELEARNING/OtherResources/ACTFLProficiencyGuidelines/contents.htm\">ACTFL Proficiency Guidelines</a>, description from SIL International</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.actfl.org/\">American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=ACTFL_Proficiency_Guidelines&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg/30px-Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg/45px-Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg/60px-Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"128\" data-file-height=\"128\" /></a></td><td><i>T